<h2>What Is a Panic Attack?</h2>
<p>A panic attack is a sudden surge of intense fear that peaks within minutes and includes physical symptoms — racing heart, shortness of breath, chest tightness, dizziness, tingling, sweating, and a sense of impending doom or unreality. Panic attacks feel life-threatening. They aren't. But they are real, distressing, and highly treatable.</p>

<p>Around 11% of adults experience at least one panic attack in any given year. For a significant portion, panic attacks become recurrent and develop into panic disorder — a condition characterised by persistent worry about future attacks and changes in behaviour to avoid them.</p>

<h2>Why Panic Attacks Happen</h2>
<p>Panic attacks are the result of the brain's threat-detection system (the amygdala) triggering a false alarm — activating the fight-or-flight response in the absence of actual danger. The body responds exactly as it would to a real threat: adrenaline surges, heart rate increases, breathing changes.</p>

<p>What makes panic disorder self-perpetuating is the catastrophic interpretation of these symptoms. The racing heart is read as a heart attack. The dizziness is read as fainting or losing control. The interpretation generates more fear, which amplifies the physical symptoms, which generates more catastrophic interpretation. Therapy breaks this cycle.</p>

<h2>Evidence-Based Treatment: CBT with Panic-Focused Exposure</h2>
<p>Cognitive Behavioral Therapy adapted for panic disorder is among the most effective psychological treatments that exists. Remission rates in well-conducted trials run 70–90%. It works through two core mechanisms:</p>

<p><strong>Psychoeducation and cognitive restructuring.</strong> Understanding what panic attacks actually are — a false alarm, not a medical emergency — dramatically reduces their intensity. Identifying and challenging the catastrophic thoughts ("I'm having a heart attack," "I'm going to lose control") removes their fuel.</p>

<p><strong>Interoceptive exposure.</strong> This is the key technique that distinguishes panic-focused CBT from generic anxiety treatment. Interoceptive exposure involves deliberately inducing the physical sensations of panic — spinning in a chair to produce dizziness, breathing through a straw to produce breathlessness, running in place to raise heart rate — in a controlled setting. Repeated exposure teaches the brain that these sensations are not dangerous. The fear response extinguishes.</p>

<p>Situational exposure is added for people who avoid places or situations where attacks have occurred (shopping centres, public transport, driving). Avoidance maintains the panic disorder even when attacks temporarily reduce.</p>

<h2>How Online Therapy Delivers This</h2>
<p>Panic-focused CBT translates well to online delivery. Psychoeducation and cognitive work are equally effective via video. Interoceptive exposure exercises are done at home under therapist guidance — which is actually an advantage, since home is where avoidance most often operates.</p>

<p>Situational exposure is also home-based by nature, making online therapy a practical fit for people whose avoidance has limited their movement significantly.</p>

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

<p><strong>Can I recover from panic disorder without medication?</strong><br/>
Yes. CBT produces remission rates comparable to medication for panic disorder, and outcomes are more durable after stopping treatment. For severe cases, the combination is more effective than either alone.</p>

<p><strong>What if I panic during a video session?</strong><br/>
A good therapist is prepared for this and uses it as a therapeutic opportunity — helping you stay with the sensations and observe that nothing catastrophic happens. It's actually useful data.</p>

<p><strong>How many sessions does it take?</strong><br/>
Significant improvement is typical within 8–12 sessions of panic-focused CBT. Many people achieve full remission within this timeframe.</p>

<p><strong>My panic attacks come out of nowhere. Does that mean therapy won't help?</strong><br/>
Nocturnal and apparently unprovoked panic attacks respond to the same treatment. "Out of nowhere" usually means the trigger is internal (a physical sensation, a thought) rather than external — interoceptive exposure addresses this directly.</p>

